"Waelbroeck C., Monfray P., Oechel W.C., Hastings S., Vourlitis G.","The impact of permafrost thawing on the carbon dynamics of tundra",1997,"Geophysical Research Letters","24","3",,"229","232",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031063188&partnerID=40&md5=3f61bf20d0a5e04cf183a878649ffaf3","Ctr. des Faibles Radioactivites, Laboratoire Mixte CNRS-CEA, Domaine du CNRS, Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA, United States; Domaine du CNRS, 91198 Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA 92182-0057, United States","Waelbroeck, C., Ctr. des Faibles Radioactivites, Laboratoire Mixte CNRS-CEA, Domaine du CNRS, Gif-sur-Yvette, France, Domaine du CNRS, 91198 Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Monfray, P., Ctr. des Faibles Radioactivites, Laboratoire Mixte CNRS-CEA, Domaine du CNRS, Gif-sur-Yvette, France, Domaine du CNRS, 91198 Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Oechel, W.C., Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA, United States, Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA 92182-0057, United States; Hastings, S., Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA, United States, Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA 92182-0057, United States; Vourlitis, G., Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA, United States, Department of Biology, San Diego State University, San Diego, CA 92182-0057, United States","There is debate on the potential release of the tundra's immense carbon stocks into the atmosphere in response to global warming. We present here results obtained with a model of CO2 exchanges, coupled to a model of the soil thermal and hydrological regime in the tundra. We show that, because of the partial thawing of permafrost and subsequent increase in nutrient availability, the ecosystem's response to warming may be a long-lasting increase in C accumulation, following a temporary increase in CO2 emissions. Our study also provides a consistent picture of CO2 exchanges in tundra ecosystems, reconciling the short-term experimental response to warming, recent field measurements, and Holocene C accumulation estimates.",,"Atmospheric composition; Carbon; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Mathematical models; Permafrost; Holocene carbon accumulation; Tundra ecosystems; Ecosystems; carbon dioxide emission; carbon storage; global warming; permafrost; tundra",,,,,,"Angell, J.K., Global, hemispheric, and zonal temperature anomalies derived from radiosonde records (1994) Trends '9, pp. 636-672. , edited by T.A. Boden, D.P. Kaiser and R.J. Sepanski, Oak Ridge, Tenn; Billings, W.D., Luken, J.O., Mortensen, D.A., Peterson, K.M., Arctic tundra: A source or sink for atmospheric carbon dioxide in a changing environment? (1982) Oecologia, 53, pp. 7-11; Brown, J., Tedrow, J.C.F., Historical developments of polar pedology and the major contributions of K.R. Everett (1996) Arctic and Alpine Research, 28, pp. 257-266; Chapman, W.L., Walsh, J.E., Recent variations of sea ice and air temperature in high latitudes (1993) Bull. Amer. Meteor. Soc., 74, pp. 33-47; Dyrness, C.T., Control of depth to permafrost and soil temperature by the forest floor in black spruce/feathermoss communities (1982) Research Note PNW-396, pp. 1-19. , US Dept. of Agriculture. Forest Service; Hansen, J., Lebedeff, S., Global trends of measured surface air temperature (1987) J. Geophys. Res., 92, pp. 13345-13372; Kane, D.L., Hinzman, L.D., Zarling, J.P., Thermal response of the active layer to climatic warming in a permafrost environment (1991) Cold Regions Science and Technology, 19, pp. 111-122; Kattenberg, A., Giorgi, F., Grassl, H., Meehl, G.A., Mitchell, J.F.B., Stoufer, R.J., Tokioka, T., Wigley, T.M.L., Climate models - Projections of future climate (1996) Climate Change 1995, pp. 285-357. , edited by J.T. Houghton, Cambridge Univ. Press; Lachenbruch, A.H., Marshall, B.V., C